answers.body_markdown:
Answer constructed with help from the official MongoDB Docs present at [this][1] link.

Your query for finding locations within **5 kilometres** should look like this:

    db.community.find({
      geolocation: {
        { $geoWithin:
          { $centerSphere: [ [ uLongitude, uLatitude ], 5 / 6378.1 ] }
        }
      }
    })

**Explanation:**

 - `$geoWithin` looks for locations within the region that is specified
   by its argument
 - `$centerSphere` is used to denote a circular region
   by specifying the center and the radius in radians
 - `5 / 6378.1` is used to convert 5 kilometers to radians. See [this][2] page for more information from the official MongoDB docs

The Docs also state:

&gt; $geoWithin does not return the documents in any specific order, so it
&gt; may show the user the furthest documents first.

To find the documents in a sorted manner use this query which is constructed using docs present at [this location][3]:

    var METERS_PER_KM = 6378.1
    db.community.find({ 
      geolocation: {
        $nearSphere: {
          $geometry: {
            type: &quot;Point&quot;,
            coordinates: [ -73.93414657, 40.82302903 ]
          },
          $maxDistance: 5 * METERS_PER_KM
        }
      }
    });

**Explanation:**

 - `$nearSphere` returns documents within the sphere of *radius*(`5 km`)
   from the *center* (`uLongitude`, `uLatitude`) in a sorted manner,
   nearest to furthest from the center.

**Edit 1:**
As per the discussion in comments, going through the MongoDB Docs, you can use an aggregation query like this one to get the distance as well:

    db.places.aggregate( [
       {
          $geoNear: {
             near: { type: &quot;Point&quot;, coordinates: [ uLongitude, uLatitude ] },
             spherical: true,
             query: {
               // Pass Any Other Query Conditions in this object
             },
             distanceField: &quot;calcDistance&quot;
          }
       }
    ] )


**Explanation:**
You can pass any other query conditions to the `query` param in the `$geoNear` stage and you should get the distance in the `calcDistance` field in the query result documents. Try following through the examples [here][5].


**Edit 2:**
To find community whose sphere range intersects with the user&#39;s coords, the community location must be stored as a `Polygon`, unfortunately, this is not true in your case, or else, you can use a simple `$geoIntersect` query. [Link to example][4]


  [1]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/tutorial/geospatial-tutorial/#find-restaurants-with-geospatial-queries
  [2]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/tutorial/calculate-distances-using-spherical-geometry-with-2d-geospatial-indexes/
  [3]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/tutorial/geospatial-tutorial/#sorted-with-nearsphere
  [4]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/query/geoIntersects/#op._S_geoIntersects
  [5]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/geospatial-queries/

