Based on the explanation (here)[https://stackoverflow.com/questions/1677415/does-stack-grow-upward-or-downward], the output makes sense.
As we allocate the new local variable `j`, the stack address reduces by 0x4. Similarly, when the function is called, there is a bigger reduction in address between outputs 2 and 3. And finally, when the function returns there is an expansion in the address (between 3 and 4).

