If the intent of the posted code is to calculate the [modified Bessel function I](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bessel_function#Modified_Bessel_functions_:_I%CE%B1,_K%CE%B1), there are some pitfalls and useful semplifications to be aware of. Given

&lt;img src=&quot;https://latex.codecogs.com/svg.latex?I_k(x)&amp;space;=&amp;space;\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}{\frac{1}{m!&amp;space;\&amp;space;\Gamma&amp;space;(m&amp;space;&amp;plus;&amp;space;k&amp;space;&amp;plus;&amp;space;1)}}\left(\frac{x}{2}&amp;space;\right&amp;space;)^{2m&amp;space;&amp;plus;&amp;space;k}&quot; title=&quot;I_k(x) = \sum_{m=0}^{\infty}{\frac{1}{m! \ \Gamma (m + k + 1)}}\left(\frac{x}{2} \right )^{2m + k}&quot; /&gt;

Trying to calculate the factorial, the value of the Gamma function, their product and the powers *separately* for each term of the sum leads to integer overflow sooner than later.

It&#39;s better to *update* the value of each addend of the sum instead. 

Also, given that `k` is a whole, we have Γ(n) = (n - 1)!

&lt;img src=&quot;https://latex.codecogs.com/svg.latex?I_k(x)&amp;space;=&amp;space;\frac{1}{k!}\left(\frac{x}{2}&amp;space;\right&amp;space;)^k&amp;space;&amp;plus;&amp;space;\frac{1}{k!}\frac{1}{k&amp;plus;1}\left(\frac{x}{2}&amp;space;\right&amp;space;)^k\left(\frac{x}{2}&amp;space;\right&amp;space;)^2&amp;space;&amp;plus;&amp;space;...&quot; title=&quot;I_k(x) = \frac{1}{k!}\left(\frac{x}{2} \right )^k + \frac{1}{k!}\frac{1}{k+1}\left(\frac{x}{2} \right )^k\left(\frac{x}{2} \right )^2 + ...&quot; /&gt;

The addends are increasingly smaller and, after some iterations, too small to be added to the sum, given the limited precision of type `double`.

```C
// Evaluates x^k / k! trying not to overflow
double power_over_factorial(double x, int k)
{
    double result = 1.0;
    for ( int i = 1; i &lt;= k; ++i )
    {
        result *= x / i;
    }
    return result;
}

#define MAX_ITERS 20

double modified_Bessel_I(int k, double x)
{
    x /= 2;
    const double xx = x * x;
    double partial = power_over_factorial(x, k);
    double old_sum, sum = partial;
    int m = 1;
    do
    {
        old_sum = sum;
        partial *= xx / ((m + k) * m);
        sum += partial;   
    }
    while ( old_sum != sum  &amp;&amp;  ++m &lt; MAX_ITERS );

    return sum;
}
```

Testable [here](https://wandbox.org/permlink/qQxa6k7kr5Bdhstu).

